{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_836349f5a0734813ac47cfd4","type":"tool_result","content":"1\tdevenv:\n2\t\tuv sync --quiet --all-extras --frozen\n3\t\tuv run pre-commit install\n4\t\n5\tinit_codespace:\n6\t\tnpm install -g @anthropic-ai/claude-code\n7\t\tgit pull || true\n8\t\tuv sync --quiet --all-extras --frozen\n9\t\n10\tload_docs_scripts:\n11\t\tif [ ! -d \"docs-scripts\" ] ; then \\\n12\t\t\tgit clone -b scripts https://github.com/Nixtla/docs.git docs-scripts --single-branch; \\\n13\t\tfi\n14\t\n15\tapi_docs:\n16\t\tpython docs/to_mdx.py docs\n17\t\n18\texamples_docs:\n19\t\tmkdir -p nbs/_extensions\n20\t\tcp -r docs-scripts/mintlify/ nbs/_extensions/mintlify\n21\t\tpython docs-scripts/update-quarto.py\n22\t\tquarto render nbs/docs --output-dir ../docs/mintlify/\n23\t\tfind docs/mintlify/docs -name \"*.mdx\" ! -name \"*.html.mdx\" -type f -exec sh -c 'mv \"$$1\" \"$${1%.mdx}.html.mdx\"' _ {} \\;\n24\t\n25\tformat_docs:\n26\t\t# replace _docs with docs\n27\t\tsed -i -e 's/_docs/docs/g' ./docs-scripts/docs-final-formatting.bash\n28\t\tbash ./docs-scripts/docs-final-formatting.bash\n29\t\tfind docs/mintlify -name \"*.mdx\" -exec sed -i.bak '/^:::/d' {} + && find docs/mintlify -name \"*.bak\" -delete\n30\t\n31\t\t# replace {'loss' with \\\\{'loss' in the hyperparam tuning notebook\n32\t\tfind docs/mintlify -name \"*.mdx\" -exec sed -i.bak \"s/{'loss'/\\\\\\\\{'loss'/g\" {} + && find docs/mintlify -name \"*.bak\" -delete\n33\t\n34\tpreview_docs:\n35\t\tcd docs/mintlify && mintlify dev\n36\t\n37\tclean:\n38\t\tfind docs/mintlify -name \"*.mdx\" -exec rm -f {} +\n39\t\n40\tcheck_links:\n41\t\t# check if mintlify is installed\n42\t\tif ! command -v mint &> /dev/null; then \\\n43\t\t\tnpm i -g mint; \\\n44\t\tfi\n45\t\tcd docs/mintlify && mintlify broken-links\n46\t\n47\tall_docs: load_docs_scripts api_docs examples_docs format_docs\n48\t\n49\tlicenses:\n50\t\tpip-licenses --format=csv --with-authors --with-urls > third_party_licenses.csv\n51\t\tpython scripts/filter_licenses.py\n52\t\trm -f third_party_licenses.csv\n53\t\t@echo \"✓ THIRD_PARTY_LICENSES.md updated\""}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"d0306c57-bea8-4dda-86c2-cd0387a8de96","uuid":"71988ebe-d5fc-4ec4-9865-9640bc789df0","timestamp":"2026-04-06T18:07:12.162Z","tool_use_result":{"type":"text","file":{"filePath":"/workspace/Makefile","content":"devenv:\n\tuv sync --quiet --all-extras --frozen\n\tuv run pre-commit install\n\ninit_codespace:\n\tnpm install -g @anthropic-ai/claude-code\n\tgit pull || true\n\tuv sync --quiet --all-extras --frozen\n\nload_docs_scripts:\n\tif [ ! -d \"docs-scripts\" ] ; then \\\n\t\tgit clone -b scripts https://github.com/Nixtla/docs.git docs-scripts --single-branch; \\\n\tfi\n\napi_docs:\n\tpython docs/to_mdx.py docs\n\nexamples_docs:\n\tmkdir -p nbs/_extensions\n\tcp -r docs-scripts/mintlify/ nbs/_extensions/mintlify\n\tpython docs-scripts/update-quarto.py\n\tquarto render nbs/docs --output-dir ../docs/mintlify/\n\tfind docs/mintlify/docs -name \"*.mdx\" ! -name \"*.html.mdx\" -type f -exec sh -c 'mv \"$$1\" \"$${1%.mdx}.html.mdx\"' _ {} \\;\n\nformat_docs:\n\t# replace _docs with docs\n\tsed -i -e 's/_docs/docs/g' ./docs-scripts/docs-final-formatting.bash\n\tbash ./docs-scripts/docs-final-formatting.bash\n\tfind docs/mintlify -name \"*.mdx\" -exec sed -i.bak '/^:::/d' {} + && find docs/mintlify -name \"*.bak\" -delete\n\n\t# replace {'loss' with \\\\{'loss' in the hyperparam tuning notebook\n\tfind docs/mintlify -name \"*.mdx\" -exec sed -i.bak \"s/{'loss'/\\\\\\\\{'loss'/g\" {} + && find docs/mintlify -name \"*.bak\" -delete\n\npreview_docs:\n\tcd docs/mintlify && mintlify dev\n\nclean:\n\tfind docs/mintlify -name \"*.mdx\" -exec rm -f {} +\n\ncheck_links:\n\t# check if mintlify is installed\n\tif ! command -v mint &> /dev/null; then \\\n\t\tnpm i -g mint; \\\n\tfi\n\tcd docs/mintlify && mintlify broken-links\n\nall_docs: load_docs_scripts api_docs examples_docs format_docs\n\nlicenses:\n\tpip-licenses --format=csv --with-authors --with-urls > third_party_licenses.csv\n\tpython scripts/filter_licenses.py\n\trm -f third_party_licenses.csv\n\t@echo \"✓ THIRD_PARTY_LICENSES.md updated\"","numLines":53,"startLine":1,"totalLines":53}}}
{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_2891385aa44f4ffc993236dd","type":"tool_result","content":"1\t[build-system]\n2\trequires = [\"setuptools>=61.0\", \"wheel\"]\n3\tbuild-backend = \"setuptools.build_meta\"\n4\t\n5\t[project]\n6\tname = \"neuralforecast\"\n7\tversion = \"3.1.6\"\n8\tdescription = \"Time series forecasting suite using deep learning models\"\n9\tauthors = [\n10\t    {name = \"Nixtla\", email = \"business@nixtla.io\"}\n11\t]\n12\tlicense = {text = \"Apache-2.0\"}\n13\treadme = \"README.md\"\n14\trequires-python = \">=3.10\"\n15\tkeywords = [\"time-series\", \"forecasting\", \"deep-learning\"]\n16\tclassifiers = [\n17\t    \"Development Status :: 4 - Beta\",\n18\t    \"Intended Audience :: Developers\",\n19\t    \"Natural Language :: English\",\n20\t    \"License :: OSI Approved :: Apache Software License\",\n21\t    \"Programming Language :: Python :: 3.10\",\n22\t    \"Programming Language :: Python :: 3.11\",\n23\t    \"Programming Language :: Python :: 3.12\",\n24\t    \"Programming Language :: Python :: 3.13\",\n25\t]\n26\tdependencies = [\n27\t    \"coreforecast>=0.0.6\",\n28\t    \"fsspec\",\n29\t    \"numpy>=1.21.6\",\n30\t    \"pandas>=1.3.5\",\n31\t    \"torch>=2.4.0\",\n32\t    \"tornado>=6.5.5\",\n33\t    \"pytorch-lightning>=2.0.0\",\n34\t    \"ray[train,tune]>=2.2.0\",\n35\t    \"optuna\",\n36\t    \"utilsforecast>=0.2.3\",\n37\t]\n38\t[project.optional-dependencies]\n39\tspark = [\"fugue\", \"pyspark>=3.5\"]\n40\t\n41\t[dependency-groups]\n42\taws = [\"fsspec[s3]\"]\n43\tdev = [\n44\t    \"black>=26.3.1\",\n45\t    \"captum\",\n46\t    \"gitpython\",\n47\t    \"hyperopt\",\n48\t    \"ipython<=8.32.0\",\n49\t    \"matplotlib\",\n50\t    \"mypy\",\n51\t    \"ninja\",\n52\t    \"polars\",\n53\t    \"pre-commit\",\n54\t    \"pyarrow\",\n55\t    \"ruff\",\n56\t    \"s3fs\",\n57\t    \"transformers\",\n58\t    \"xlstm\",\n59\t    \"pytest\",\n60\t    \"pytest-cov\",\n61\t    \"pip-licenses\",\n62\t    \"mkdocstrings-parser @ git+https://github.com/Nixtla/mkdocstrings-parser@main\"\n63\t]\n64\t\n65\t[project.urls]\n66\tHomepage = \"https://github.com/Nixtla/neuralforecast/\"\n67\tDocumentation = \"https://nixtlaverse.nixtla.io/neuralforecast/\"\n68\t\n69\t[tool.setuptools]\n70\tpackages = [\"neuralforecast\"]\n71\t\n72\t[tool.ruff]\n73\ttarget-version = \"py310\"\n74\tline-length = 88\n75\tlint.select = [\"F\"]\n76\t\n77\t[tool.mypy]\n78\tignore_missing_imports = true\n79\t\n80\t[[tool.mypy.overrides]]\n81\tmodule = 'neuralforecast.compat'\n82\tignore_errors = true\n83\t\n84\t[tool.pytest.ini_options]\n85\ttestpaths = [\"tests\"]\n86\taddopts = [\n87\t    \"--cov=neuralforecast\",\n88\t    \"--cov-report=term-missing\",\n89\t    \"--cov-report=html\",\n90\t    \"--cov-fail-under=80\",\n91\t]\n92\t\n93\t[tool.coverage.run]\n94\tsource = [\"neuralforecast\"]\n95\tomit = [\n96\t    \"*/tmp/ray/*\",\n97\t    \"*/_ray_pkg_*/*\",\n98\t    \"*/runtime_resources/*\",\n99\t]\n100\t\n101\t[tool.coverage.report]\n102\tomit = [\n103\t    \"*/tmp/ray/*\",\n104\t    \"*/_ray_pkg_*/*\",\n105\t    \"*/runtime_resources/*\",\n106\t]\n107\t"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"d0306c57-bea8-4dda-86c2-cd0387a8de96","uuid":"30b48723-a26f-4de8-93b1-f53c4f6df805","timestamp":"2026-04-06T18:07:12.164Z","tool_use_result":{"type":"text","file":{"filePath":"/workspace/pyproject.toml","content":"[build-system]\nrequires = [\"setuptools>=61.0\", \"wheel\"]\nbuild-backend = \"setuptools.build_meta\"\n\n[project]\nname = \"neuralforecast\"\nversion = \"3.1.6\"\ndescription = \"Time series forecasting suite using deep learning models\"\nauthors = [\n    {name = \"Nixtla\", email = \"business@nixtla.io\"}\n]\nlicense = {text = \"Apache-2.0\"}\nreadme = \"README.md\"\nrequires-python = \">=3.10\"\nkeywords = [\"time-series\", \"forecasting\", \"deep-learning\"]\nclassifiers = [\n    \"Development Status :: 4 - Beta\",\n    \"Intended Audience :: Developers\",\n    \"Natural Language :: English\",\n    \"License :: OSI Approved :: Apache Software License\",\n    \"Programming Language :: Python :: 3.10\",\n    \"Programming Language :: Python :: 3.11\",\n    \"Programming Language :: Python :: 3.12\",\n    \"Programming Language :: Python :: 3.13\",\n]\ndependencies = [\n    \"coreforecast>=0.0.6\",\n    \"fsspec\",\n    \"numpy>=1.21.6\",\n    \"pandas>=1.3.5\",\n    \"torch>=2.4.0\",\n    \"tornado>=6.5.5\",\n    \"pytorch-lightning>=2.0.0\",\n    \"ray[train,tune]>=2.2.0\",\n    \"optuna\",\n    \"utilsforecast>=0.2.3\",\n]\n[project.optional-dependencies]\nspark = [\"fugue\", \"pyspark>=3.5\"]\n\n[dependency-groups]\naws = [\"fsspec[s3]\"]\ndev = [\n    \"black>=26.3.1\",\n    \"captum\",\n    \"gitpython\",\n    \"hyperopt\",\n    \"ipython<=8.32.0\",\n    \"matplotlib\",\n    \"mypy\",\n    \"ninja\",\n    \"polars\",\n    \"pre-commit\",\n    \"pyarrow\",\n    \"ruff\",\n    \"s3fs\",\n    \"transformers\",\n    \"xlstm\",\n    \"pytest\",\n    \"pytest-cov\",\n    \"pip-licenses\",\n    \"mkdocstrings-parser @ git+https://github.com/Nixtla/mkdocstrings-parser@main\"\n]\n\n[project.urls]\nHomepage = \"https://github.com/Nixtla/neuralforecast/\"\nDocumentation = \"https://nixtlaverse.nixtla.io/neuralforecast/\"\n\n[tool.setuptools]\npackages = [\"neuralforecast\"]\n\n[tool.ruff]\ntarget-version = \"py310\"\nline-length = 88\nlint.select = [\"F\"]\n\n[tool.mypy]\nignore_missing_imports = true\n\n[[tool.mypy.overrides]]\nmodule = 'neuralforecast.compat'\nignore_errors = true\n\n[tool.pytest.ini_options]\ntestpaths = [\"tests\"]\naddopts = [\n    \"--cov=neuralforecast\",\n    \"--cov-report=term-missing\",\n    \"--cov-report=html\",\n    \"--cov-fail-under=80\",\n]\n\n[tool.coverage.run]\nsource = [\"neuralforecast\"]\nomit = [\n    \"*/tmp/ray/*\",\n    \"*/_ray_pkg_*/*\",\n    \"*/runtime_resources/*\",\n]\n\n[tool.coverage.report]\nomit = [\n    \"*/tmp/ray/*\",\n    \"*/_ray_pkg_*/*\",\n    \"*/runtime_resources/*\",\n]\n","numLines":107,"startLine":1,"totalLines":107}}}
{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_54e1ef48fe65414d85e3f3b8","type":"tool_result","content":"1\t# How to contribute\n2\t\n3\t## Did you find a bug?\n4\t\n5\t* Ensure the bug was not already reported by searching on GitHub under Issues.\n6\t* If you're unable to find an open issue addressing the problem, open a new one. Be sure to include a title and clear description, as much relevant information as possible, and a code sample or an executable test case demonstrating the expected behavior that is not occurring.\n7\t* Be sure to add the complete error messages.\n8\t\n9\t## Do you have a feature request?\n10\t\n11\t* Ensure that it hasn't been yet implemented in the `main` branch of the repository and that there's not an Issue requesting it yet.\n12\t* Open a new issue and make sure to describe it clearly, mention how it improves the project and why its useful.\n13\t\n14\t## Do you want to fix a bug or implement a feature?\n15\t\n16\tBug fixes and features are added through pull requests (PRs).\n17\t\n18\t## PR submission guidelines\n19\t\n20\t* Keep each PR focused. While it's more convenient, do not combine several unrelated fixes together. Create as many branches as needing to keep each PR focused.\n21\t* Ensure that your PR includes a test that fails without your patch, and passes with it.\n22\t* Ensure the PR description clearly describes the problem and solution. Include the relevant issue number if applicable.\n23\t* Do not mix style changes/fixes with \"functional\" changes. It's very difficult to review such PRs and it most likely get rejected.\n24\t* Do not add/remove vertical whitespace. Preserve the original style of the file you edit as much as you can.\n25\t* Do not turn an already submitted PR into your development playground. If after you submitted PR, you discovered that more work is needed - close the PR, do the required work and then submit a new PR. Otherwise each of your commits requires attention from maintainers of the project.\n26\t* If, however, you submitted a PR and received a request for changes, you should proceed with commits inside that PR, so that the maintainer can see the incremental fixes and won't need to review the whole PR again. In the exception case where you realize it'll take many many commits to complete the requests, then it's probably best to close the PR, do the work and then submit it again. Use common sense where you'd choose one way over another.\n27\t\n28\t### Local setup for working on a PR\n29\t\n30\t#### Fork and clone the repository\n31\t\n32\t1. **Fork the repository**: Navigate to the [neuralforecast repository](https://github.com/Nixtla/neuralforecast) and click the \"Fork\" button in the top-right corner. This creates a copy of the repository under your GitHub account.\n33\t\n34\t2. **Clone your fork**: Clone your forked repository to your local machine (replace `YOUR_USERNAME` with your GitHub username):\n35\t\n36\t   * HTTPS: `git clone https://github.com/YOUR_USERNAME/neuralforecast.git`\n37\t   * SSH: `git clone git@github.com:YOUR_USERNAME/neuralforecast.git`\n38\t   * GitHub CLI: `gh repo clone YOUR_USERNAME/neuralforecast`\n39\t\n40\t3. **Navigate to the project directory**:\n41\t\n42\t   ```bash\n43\t   cd neuralforecast\n44\t   ```\n45\t\n46\t4. **Add the upstream remote** (Optional - skip if you prefer using GitHub's web UI): Add the original Nixtla repository as an upstream remote to keep your fork in sync:\n47\t\n48\t   ```bash\n49\t   git remote add upstream https://github.com/Nixtla/neuralforecast.git\n50\t   ```\n51\t\n52\t   > **Note**: This step is not required if you use GitHub's \"Sync fork\" button in the web UI to keep your fork updated. However, configuring the upstream remote is recommended for a smoother local development workflow.\n53\t\n54\t5. **Verify your remotes**: Confirm that you have both `origin` (your fork) and `upstream` (original repo) configured:\n55\t\n56\t   ```bash\n57\t   git remote -v\n58\t   ```\n59\t\n60\t6. **Keep your fork up to date**: Before starting work on a new feature or fix, sync your fork with the upstream repository:\n61\t\n62\t   **Option A - Using Git locally** (requires step 4):\n63\t   ```bash\n64\t   git checkout main\n65\t   git fetch upstream\n66\t   git merge upstream/main\n67\t   git push origin main\n68\t   ```\n69\t\n70\t   **Option B - Using GitHub's web UI**: Navigate to your fork on GitHub and click the \"Sync fork\" button, then pull the changes locally:\n71\t   ```bash\n72\t   git checkout main\n73\t   git pull origin main\n74\t   ```\n75\t\n76\t7. **Create a feature branch**: Always create a new branch for your work:\n77\t\n78\t   ```bash\n79\t   git checkout -b your-feature-branch-name\n80\t   ```\n81\t\n82\t#### Set up an environment\n83\t\n84\tCreate a virtual environment to install the library's dependencies. We recommend [astral's uv](https://github.com/astral-sh/uv).\n85\tOnce you've created the virtual environment you should activate it and then install the library in editable mode along with its development dependencies.\n86\t\n87\tInstall `uv` and create a virtual environment:\n88\t\n89\t```bash\n90\tpip install uv\n91\tuv venv --python 3.11\n92\t```\n93\t\n94\tThen, activate the virtual environment:\n95\t\n96\t* On Linux/MacOS:\n97\t\n98\t```bash\n99\tsource .venv/bin/activate\n100\t```\n101\t\n102\t* On Windows:\n103\t\n104\t```bash\n105\t.\\.venv\\Scripts\\activate\n106\t```\n107\t\n108\tNow, install the library. Make sure to specify the desired [PyTorch backend](https://docs.astral.sh/uv/reference/cli/#uv-sync--torch-backend):\n109\t\n110\t```bash\n111\tuv sync --group dev --torch-backend auto # uv will decide the optimal backend automatically\n112\tuv sync --group dev --torch-backend cpu # for cpu backend\n113\tuv sync --group dev --torch-backend cu118 # for CUDA 11.8 PyTorch backend\n114\t```\n115\t\n116\tYou can install other optional dependencies:\n117\t\n118\t```sh\n119\tuv sync --group dev --group aws --extra spark\n120\t```\n121\t\n122\t#### Install pre-commit hooks\n123\t\n124\t```sh\n125\tpre-commit install\n126\tpre-commit run --files neuralforecast/*\n127\t```\n128\t\n129\t#### Running tests\n130\t\n131\tTo run the tests:\n132\t\n133\t```sh\n134\tuv run pytest\n135\t```\n136\t\n137\t#### Submitting your changes\n138\t\n139\tAfter making your changes and testing them:\n140\t\n141\t1. **Commit your changes**: Make sure your commits are clear and descriptive:\n142\t\n143\t   ```bash\n144\t   git add .\n145\t   git commit -m \"Description of your changes\"\n146\t   ```\n147\t\n148\t2. **Push to your fork**: Push your feature branch to your forked repository:\n149\t\n150\t   ```bash\n151\t   git push origin your-feature-branch-name\n152\t   ```\n153\t\n154\t3. **Create a Pull Request**: Go to the [original neuralforecast repository](https://github.com/Nixtla/neuralforecast) and you should see a prompt to create a pull request from your recently pushed branch. Click on \"Compare & pull request\" and fill in the PR details following the guidelines above.\n155\t\n156\t4. **Keep your PR updated**: If you need to make changes based on review feedback, commit and push to the same branch:\n157\t\n158\t   ```bash\n159\t   git add .\n160\t   git commit -m \"Address review comments\"\n161\t   git push origin your-feature-branch-name\n162\t   ```\n163\t\n164\t   The PR will automatically update with your new commits.\n165\t\n166\t#### Viewing documentation locally\n167\t\n168\tThe documentation pipeline relies on `quarto`, `mintlify` and `griffe2md`.\n169\t\n170\t**Install Quarto:**\n171\t\n172\tInstall `quarto` from [the official website](https://quarto.org/docs/get-started/)\n173\t\n174\t**Install Mintlify:**\n175\t\n176\t> [!NOTE]\n177\t> Please install Node.js before proceeding.\n178\t\n179\t```bash\n180\tnpm i -g mint\n181\t```\n182\t\n183\tFor additional instructions, see the [Mintlify installation guide](https://mintlify.com/docs/installation).\n184\t\n185\t**Install documentation dependencies:**\n186\t\n187\t```sh\n188\tuv sync --group dev --group aws --extra spark\n189\t```\n190\t\n191\t**Generate documentation:**\n192\t\n193\t```bash\n194\tmake all_docs\n195\t```\n196\t\n197\t**Preview documentation locally:**\n198\t\n199\t```bash\n200\tmake preview_docs\n201\t```\n202\t\n203\t## Do you want to contribute to the documentation?\n204\t\n205\t* The docs are automatically generated from the docstrings in the `neuralforecast` folder.\n206\t* To contribute, ensure your docstrings follow the Google style format.\n207\t* Once your docstring is correctly written, the documentation framework will scrape it and regenerate the corresponding `.mdx` files and your changes will then appear in the updated docs.\n208\t* For examples and how-to-guides, make sure you submit clean notebooks with cleared outputs, formatted LaTeX, links and images.\n209\t* Make an appropriate entry in the `docs/mintlify/docs.json` file.\n210\t* Run `make all_docs` to regenerate the documentation.\n211\t* Run `make preview_docs` to view and test the documentation locally.\n212\t\n213\t### Example google-style docstring\n214\t\n215\t```py\n216\tdef function_name(parameter1, parameter2):\n217\t    \"\"\"Brief summary of the function's purpose.\n218\t\n219\t    Detailed explanation of what the function does, its behavior, and any\n220\t    important considerations. This section can span multiple lines.\n221\t\n222\t    Args:\n223\t        parameter1 (type): Description of parameter1.\n224\t        parameter2 (type): Description of parameter2.\n225\t\n226\t    Returns:\n227\t        type: Description of the return value.\n228\t\n229\t    Raises:\n230\t        ExceptionType: Description of the circumstances under which this\n231\t                       exception is raised.\n232\t\n233\t    Example:\n234\t        Examples can be provided to demonstrate how to use the function.\n235\t        Literal blocks can be included for code snippets::\n236\t\n237\t            result = function_name(10, 'hello')\n238\t            print(result)\n239\t\n240\t    Notes:\n241\t        Any additional notes or important information.\n242\t    \"\"\"\n243\t    # Function implementation\n244\t    pass\n245\t\n246\t```\n247\t"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"d0306c57-bea8-4dda-86c2-cd0387a8de96","uuid":"4c3d649f-059d-42b9-8107-7431987d712d","timestamp":"2026-04-06T18:07:12.165Z","tool_use_result":{"type":"text","file":{"filePath":"/workspace/CONTRIBUTING.md","content":"# How to contribute\n\n## Did you find a bug?\n\n* Ensure the bug was not already reported by searching on GitHub under Issues.\n* If you're unable to find an open issue addressing the problem, open a new one. Be sure to include a title and clear description, as much relevant information as possible, and a code sample or an executable test case demonstrating the expected behavior that is not occurring.\n* Be sure to add the complete error messages.\n\n## Do you have a feature request?\n\n* Ensure that it hasn't been yet implemented in the `main` branch of the repository and that there's not an Issue requesting it yet.\n* Open a new issue and make sure to describe it clearly, mention how it improves the project and why its useful.\n\n## Do you want to fix a bug or implement a feature?\n\nBug fixes and features are added through pull requests (PRs).\n\n## PR submission guidelines\n\n* Keep each PR focused. While it's more convenient, do not combine several unrelated fixes together. Create as many branches as needing to keep each PR focused.\n* Ensure that your PR includes a test that fails without your patch, and passes with it.\n* Ensure the PR description clearly describes the problem and solution. Include the relevant issue number if applicable.\n* Do not mix style changes/fixes with \"functional\" changes. It's very difficult to review such PRs and it most likely get rejected.\n* Do not add/remove vertical whitespace. Preserve the original style of the file you edit as much as you can.\n* Do not turn an already submitted PR into your development playground. If after you submitted PR, you discovered that more work is needed - close the PR, do the required work and then submit a new PR. Otherwise each of your commits requires attention from maintainers of the project.\n* If, however, you submitted a PR and received a request for changes, you should proceed with commits inside that PR, so that the maintainer can see the incremental fixes and won't need to review the whole PR again. In the exception case where you realize it'll take many many commits to complete the requests, then it's probably best to close the PR, do the work and then submit it again. Use common sense where you'd choose one way over another.\n\n### Local setup for working on a PR\n\n#### Fork and clone the repository\n\n1. **Fork the repository**: Navigate to the [neuralforecast repository](https://github.com/Nixtla/neuralforecast) and click the \"Fork\" button in the top-right corner. This creates a copy of the repository under your GitHub account.\n\n2. **Clone your fork**: Clone your forked repository to your local machine (replace `YOUR_USERNAME` with your GitHub username):\n\n   * HTTPS: `git clone https://github.com/YOUR_USERNAME/neuralforecast.git`\n   * SSH: `git clone git@github.com:YOUR_USERNAME/neuralforecast.git`\n   * GitHub CLI: `gh repo clone YOUR_USERNAME/neuralforecast`\n\n3. **Navigate to the project directory**:\n\n   ```bash\n   cd neuralforecast\n   ```\n\n4. **Add the upstream remote** (Optional - skip if you prefer using GitHub's web UI): Add the original Nixtla repository as an upstream remote to keep your fork in sync:\n\n   ```bash\n   git remote add upstream https://github.com/Nixtla/neuralforecast.git\n   ```\n\n   > **Note**: This step is not required if you use GitHub's \"Sync fork\" button in the web UI to keep your fork updated. However, configuring the upstream remote is recommended for a smoother local development workflow.\n\n5. **Verify your remotes**: Confirm that you have both `origin` (your fork) and `upstream` (original repo) configured:\n\n   ```bash\n   git remote -v\n   ```\n\n6. **Keep your fork up to date**: Before starting work on a new feature or fix, sync your fork with the upstream repository:\n\n   **Option A - Using Git locally** (requires step 4):\n   ```bash\n   git checkout main\n   git fetch upstream\n   git merge upstream/main\n   git push origin main\n   ```\n\n   **Option B - Using GitHub's web UI**: Navigate to your fork on GitHub and click the \"Sync fork\" button, then pull the changes locally:\n   ```bash\n   git checkout main\n   git pull origin main\n   ```\n\n7. **Create a feature branch**: Always create a new branch for your work:\n\n   ```bash\n   git checkout -b your-feature-branch-name\n   ```\n\n#### Set up an environment\n\nCreate a virtual environment to install the library's dependencies. We recommend [astral's uv](https://github.com/astral-sh/uv).\nOnce you've created the virtual environment you should activate it and then install the library in editable mode along with its development dependencies.\n\nInstall `uv` and create a virtual environment:\n\n```bash\npip install uv\nuv venv --python 3.11\n```\n\nThen, activate the virtual environment:\n\n* On Linux/MacOS:\n\n```bash\nsource .venv/bin/activate\n```\n\n* On Windows:\n\n```bash\n.\\.venv\\Scripts\\activate\n```\n\nNow, install the library. Make sure to specify the desired [PyTorch backend](https://docs.astral.sh/uv/reference/cli/#uv-sync--torch-backend):\n\n```bash\nuv sync --group dev --torch-backend auto # uv will decide the optimal backend automatically\nuv sync --group dev --torch-backend cpu # for cpu backend\nuv sync --group dev --torch-backend cu118 # for CUDA 11.8 PyTorch backend\n```\n\nYou can install other optional dependencies:\n\n```sh\nuv sync --group dev --group aws --extra spark\n```\n\n#### Install pre-commit hooks\n\n```sh\npre-commit install\npre-commit run --files neuralforecast/*\n```\n\n#### Running tests\n\nTo run the tests:\n\n```sh\nuv run pytest\n```\n\n#### Submitting your changes\n\nAfter making your changes and testing them:\n\n1. **Commit your changes**: Make sure your commits are clear and descriptive:\n\n   ```bash\n   git add .\n   git commit -m \"Description of your changes\"\n   ```\n\n2. **Push to your fork**: Push your feature branch to your forked repository:\n\n   ```bash\n   git push origin your-feature-branch-name\n   ```\n\n3. **Create a Pull Request**: Go to the [original neuralforecast repository](https://github.com/Nixtla/neuralforecast) and you should see a prompt to create a pull request from your recently pushed branch. Click on \"Compare & pull request\" and fill in the PR details following the guidelines above.\n\n4. **Keep your PR updated**: If you need to make changes based on review feedback, commit and push to the same branch:\n\n   ```bash\n   git add .\n   git commit -m \"Address review comments\"\n   git push origin your-feature-branch-name\n   ```\n\n   The PR will automatically update with your new commits.\n\n#### Viewing documentation locally\n\nThe documentation pipeline relies on `quarto`, `mintlify` and `griffe2md`.\n\n**Install Quarto:**\n\nInstall `quarto` from [the official website](https://quarto.org/docs/get-started/)\n\n**Install Mintlify:**\n\n> [!NOTE]\n> Please install Node.js before proceeding.\n\n```bash\nnpm i -g mint\n```\n\nFor additional instructions, see the [Mintlify installation guide](https://mintlify.com/docs/installation).\n\n**Install documentation dependencies:**\n\n```sh\nuv sync --group dev --group aws --extra spark\n```\n\n**Generate documentation:**\n\n```bash\nmake all_docs\n```\n\n**Preview documentation locally:**\n\n```bash\nmake preview_docs\n```\n\n## Do you want to contribute to the documentation?\n\n* The docs are automatically generated from the docstrings in the `neuralforecast` folder.\n* To contribute, ensure your docstrings follow the Google style format.\n* Once your docstring is correctly written, the documentation framework will scrape it and regenerate the corresponding `.mdx` files and your changes will then appear in the updated docs.\n* For examples and how-to-guides, make sure you submit clean notebooks with cleared outputs, formatted LaTeX, links and images.\n* Make an appropriate entry in the `docs/mintlify/docs.json` file.\n* Run `make all_docs` to regenerate the documentation.\n* Run `make preview_docs` to view and test the documentation locally.\n\n### Example google-style docstring\n\n```py\ndef function_name(parameter1, parameter2):\n    \"\"\"Brief summary of the function's purpose.\n\n    Detailed explanation of what the function does, its behavior, and any\n    important considerations. This section can span multiple lines.\n\n    Args:\n        parameter1 (type): Description of parameter1.\n        parameter2 (type): Description of parameter2.\n\n    Returns:\n        type: Description of the return value.\n\n    Raises:\n        ExceptionType: Description of the circumstances under which this\n                       exception is raised.\n\n    Example:\n        Examples can be provided to demonstrate how to use the function.\n        Literal blocks can be included for code snippets::\n\n            result = function_name(10, 'hello')\n            print(result)\n\n    Notes:\n        Any additional notes or important information.\n    \"\"\"\n    # Function implementation\n    pass\n\n```\n","numLines":247,"startLine":1,"totalLines":247}}}
